english:
  title: Record of the Celestial Map
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The stone tablet of the Celestial Map once stood in Pyongyang, but was lost to the waters when strife swept the land. With years upon years passing, even its printed copies have vanished entirely. Only when our Lord received the Mandate did someone present a single volume, which His Highness treasured greatly.

    He commanded the Bureau of Astronomy to carve it anew upon stone. The Bureau reported that the map, worn by time, showed stars shifted from their true positions. They advised taking fresh measurements to establish the central stars for the solstices and equinoxes, creating a new map for posterity. The Lord approved, and in the sixth month of that year, the Bureau submitted their revised Celestial Record. In the old map, the Pleiades marked the midpoint of spring's beginning at dusk, but now the stars of the Stomach constellation hold that place. The twenty-four solar periods had drifted in sequence. Thus the old map was corrected, and when the carving was complete, His Highness commanded me to record this afterward.

    I humbly reflect that since ancient times, no sage-king governing under Heaven has failed to make the calendar and celestial observation his first priority. Yao commissioned the Astronomers to order the seasons; Shun consulted the celestial sphere to harmonize the Seven Governors. This was because reverence for Heaven and diligence toward the people admit no delay. Observing our Lord—wise and virtuous, having received the realm through succession—the realm enjoys peace, touching the heights of harmony. This is the virtue of Yao and Shun. In first examining the heavens to correct the central stars, He practices their governance. Yet if we seek the heart with which Yao and Shun observed the patterns and fashioned their instruments, its foundation rests solely on reverence. Our Lord likewise holds reverence in His heart, honoring the celestial seasons above and attending diligently to the people's affairs below. Thus shall His divine accomplishments shine forth equal to those two sage-kings. And this map, graven upon eternal stone, shall become the treasure of His descendants for ten thousand generations. How true this is!
  footnotes:
    - The Bureau of Astronomy (書雲觀) was the royal institution responsible for astronomical observation and calendrical calculations in the Joseon dynasty.
    - 'The ''seven governors'' (七政) refer to the celestial bodies used to regulate the calendar: the sun, moon, and five planets.'
    - Yao and Shun were legendary sage-kings of ancient China known for their virtue and wise governance, the archetypal models for benevolent rulership in Confucian thought.
